Boomi confirms sign-in by validating the Entra JWT (signature, issuer, audience, expiry, access_as_user scope) and the x-api-key. That proves a real signed-in user hit your Boomi endpoint. Boomi then calls the Function as itself with a service token, passing userId as the Dataverse identity for impersonation.


How Boomi confirms (gateway validation)
Typical Boomi REST/API setup for this pattern:

1. x-api-key (API gateway)
Boomi checks the header against a configured key.
Confirms the call is from your D365 integration (shared secret), not random internet traffic.
Does not identify the user — only that the client knows the gateway key.
2. Authorization: Bearer (user JWT)
Boomi (or an OAuth/JWT step in the process) validates the access token, usually:

Check	What it proves
Signature
Token was issued by Entra (tenant signing keys)
Issuer (iss)
From your tenant’s login endpoint
Audience (aud)
Intended for your API app (api://<ApiAppId> or similar)
Expiry (exp)
Token is still valid
Scope (scp)
Includes access_as_user (delegated permission)

If any of that fails → Boomi returns 401/403 and never calls the Azure Function.

That’s what “confirm who signed in at the gateway” means: a valid Entra user token for your API, not “Boomi trusts the userId query param by itself.”
